```json
{
  "idea": {
    "Name": "dynamic_rate_distortion_compression",
    "Title": "Dynamic Rate-Distortion Compression for Adaptive Learning",
    "Short Hypothesis": "Dynamic quantization based on real-time activation statistics can optimize model compression while minimizing task-relevant distortion, outperforming static quantization methods in scenarios with distributional shifts.",
    "Related Work": "Existing methods like 'Radio' focus on static quantization strategies. In contrast, our proposal leverages real-time activation statistics to adaptively adjust quantization levels, ensuring better performance under varying input distributions, thus addressing limitations in robustness and efficiency found in previous works.",
    "Abstract": "In this work, we propose a novel framework for model compression that dynamically adjusts quantization levels based on real-time activation statistics, grounded in rate-distortion theory. Our hypothesis is that by correlating the distortion caused by quantization with the statistical properties of model activations, we can achieve a more efficient compression strategy that maintains predictive performance even under distributional shifts. We will rigorously evaluate the proposed method against static quantization baselines through a series of experiments that measure task-relevant distortion and efficiency. Our approach promises to bridge the gap between theoretical limits of compression and practical applications in machine learning, offering a reproducible, information-theoretic foundation for adaptive model compression.",
    "Experiments": [
      "1. Implement a baseline static quantization scheme for a standard neural network architecture.",
      "2. Develop the dynamic quantization method based on real-time activation statistics.",
